Comparative Genomics/Plasmids Analysis: Scatter Plots

Brian Smith

7/17/2017

Collect Data

Read in data and manipulate

library("ggplot2")

raw_data <- read.csv(file_path, sep = "\t")
#Translates/Reverses rows and columns
data <- t(raw_data)
df <- as.data.frame(data)
df_final <- df[-c(1), ]
df_final$V1 <- as.numeric(as.character(df_final$V1))
df_final$V2 <- as.numeric(as.character(df_final$V2))
df_final$V3 <- as.numeric(as.character(df_final$V3))
df_final$V4 <- as.numeric(as.character(df_final$V4))
colnames(df_final)[1] <- "Lac107 Chromosome"
colnames(df_final)[2] <- "pMPPlac107"
colnames(df_final)[3] <- "Leaf58 Chromosome"
colnames(df_final)[4] <- "Leaf58 Contig"

Tetranucleotide Frequencies

Each scatter plot is composed of tetranucleotide frequencies corresponding to axis label. The blue line is a linear regression model and the shaded area surrounding the line is a 95% confidence interval for that model.

ggplot(df_final, aes(x=pMPPlac107, y=`Leaf58 Contig`)) + geom_point(shape = 1) + geom_smooth(method = lm)

Additionally you can remove the defualt background and enlarge the axis lines by calling theme and editing its options.

ggplot(df_final, aes(x=pMPPlac107, y=`Leaf58 Contig`)) + geom_point(shape = 1) + geom_smooth(method = lm) + theme(axis.line = element_line(size = 1, colour = "black"), panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"))
